NOTES_1TIMOTHY = {
    1: {
        1: 'GREEK: "Apostolos" (ἀπόστολος, Strong\'s G652) denotes one sent with delegated authority, not merely a messenger. "Kat\' epitagēn" (κατ\' ἐπιταγήν) means "according to command"—Paul\'s apostleship rests on divine mandate, not self-appointment. THEOLOGICAL: God is here called "Savior" (sōtēr, σωτήρ), a title shared between the Father and Christ Jesus in the Pastoral Epistles, underscoring the unity of the divine saving purpose (cf. Titus 2:13).',
        4: 'GREEK: "Genealogíais aperántois" (γενεαλογίαις ἀπεράντοις)—"endless genealogies"—likely refers to speculative expansions of OT genealogies in Second Temple Jewish tradition or early proto-gnostic aeon lists. "Oikonomían theoú" (οἰκονομίαν θεοῦ) means "the stewardship/administration of God," pointing to God\'s ordered plan of salvation rather than human speculation. HISTORICAL: Ephesus was a crossroads of Jewish and Hellenistic speculation; the false teachers likely blended Torah interpretation with mythological elaboration.',
        5: 'THEOLOGICAL: The "télos" (τέλος) of the charge is not merely its cessation but its purpose and goal—love (agápē). This love has a threefold source: a pure heart, a good conscience, and unhypocritical faith (písteos anypokrítou). GREEK: "Anypókritos" (ἀνυπόκριτος, G505) means "without hypocrisy, unfeigned"—a key Pauline qualifier for genuine faith and love (cf. Rom 12:9; 2 Cor 6:6).',
        9: 'GREEK: "Dikaiō nómos ou keîtai" (δικαίῳ νόμος οὐ κεῖται)—the law "is not laid down" or "does not lie appointed" for the righteous. "Keîtai" suggests a law set in place as a restraint. The vice list that follows echoes the structure of the Decalogue, moving from offenses against God to offenses against neighbor. THEOLOGICAL: Paul does not abrogate the law but clarifies its function: it convicts the lawless, not those already walking in faith and love (cf. Gal 3:19-25).',
        10: 'GREEK: "Arsenokoítais" (ἀρσενοκοίταις, G733) is a compound from "arsēn" (male) and "koítē" (bed), likely coined from the LXX of Lev 18:22 and 20:13 (meta arsenos koitēn). "Andrapodistais" (ἀνδραποδισταῖς, G405) denotes slave-traders or kidnappers who enslave free persons—a hapax legomenon in the NT. HISTORICAL: Slave-trading was condemned in Jewish law (Exod 21:16; Deut 24:7) and its inclusion here aligns the vice list with Torah categories.',
        11: 'THEOLOGICAL: "The gospel of the glory of the blessed God" is a remarkable genitive chain: the gospel is itself the radiance of God\'s glory, not merely a report about it. "Makaríou" (μακαρίου) applied to God is rare in the NT (cf. 1 Tim 6:15), emphasizing God\'s transcendent blessedness. Paul\'s entrustment (episteúthēn, passive of pisteúō) stresses that the gospel is a divine deposit, not a human invention.',
        14: 'GREEK: "Hyperepleonasen" (ὑπερεπλεόνασεν, G5250) is a hapax legomenon in the NT—an intensified compound meaning "super-abounded" or "overflowed beyond all measure." The prefix hyper- intensifies the already strong pleonázō. TYPOLOGY: This mirrors Paul\'s principle in Rom 5:20: "where sin increased, grace super-abounded," with Paul\'s own life as the living demonstration.',
        15: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Pistós ho lógos" (πιστὸς ὁ λόγος)—"Faithful is the word"—is a distinctive formula appearing five times in the Pastoral Epistles, introducing core confessional statements. This is the first and arguably most central: Christ Jesus came into the world to save sinners. TYPOLOGY: Christ\'s entrance "into the world" (eis ton kosmon) echoes the incarnational theology of John 1:9-14 and the divine mission from heaven to earth (cf. Phil 2:6-8). Paul\'s self-designation as "foremost" (prōtos) of sinners is not rhetorical humility but genuine theological conviction grounding the universality of grace.',
        17: 'THEOLOGICAL: This doxology ascribes four attributes to God: King of the ages (basileî tōn aiṓnōn), immortal (aphthártō), invisible (aorátō), only God (mónō theō). DIVINE_COUNCIL: "King of the ages" positions God as sovereign over all temporal and cosmic epochs, ruling over all heavenly and earthly powers. "Mónō theō" (the only God) does not deny the divine identity of Christ but affirms monotheistic ontology within which Christ operates as Lord—consistent with the Shema framework (Deut 6:4) as applied in 1 Cor 8:6. The doxological formula "unto the ages of the ages" (eis tous aiōnas tōn aiōnōn) is the strongest Greek expression of eternity.',
        20: 'GREEK: "Parédōka tō Satanâ" (παρέδωκα τῷ Σατανᾷ)—"I delivered over to Satan"—parallels 1 Cor 5:5 and likely denotes formal excommunication, placing the offender outside the protective boundary of the ekklēsia and into the domain of the adversary. THEOLOGICAL: The purpose is remedial, not destructive: "hína paideuthōsi" (ἵνα παιδευθῶσι)—"that they might be disciplined." Paideúō (G3811) carries the sense of child-training and correction, indicating hope for restoration. HISTORICAL: Hymenaeus reappears in 2 Tim 2:17 still teaching falsely; Alexander may be the coppersmith of 2 Tim 4:14.',
    },
    2: {
        1: 'GREEK: Paul uses four distinct terms for prayer: δεήσεις (deēseis, Strong\'s G1162) — specific petitions arising from need; προσευχάς (proseuchas, G4335) — general prayers directed to God; ἐντεύξεις (enteuxeis, G1783) — intercessions, literally "meetings with" or "petitions to a superior," used only here and in 1 Tim 4:5 in the NT; and εὐχαριστίας (eucharistias, G2169) — thanksgivings. The breadth of terms emphasizes the comprehensive nature of the prayer life commanded.',
        4: 'THEOLOGICAL: The phrase πάντας ἀνθρώπους θέλει σωθῆναι ("desires all men to be saved") uses θέλει (thelei, G2309), expressing God\'s volitional desire. The word ἐπίγνωσιν (epignōsin, G1922) is not mere γνῶσις (gnōsis, "knowledge") but a full, experiential, precise knowledge of truth. This verse grounds the universal scope of prayer in verses 1-2 in the universal salvific will of God (cf. 2 Pet 3:9; Titus 2:11).',
        5: 'THEOLOGICAL: The emphatic εἷς... εἷς ("one... one") echoes the Shema of Deut 6:4 (LXX: εἷς ἐστιν) and applies monotheistic logic to the mediatorial office of Christ. GREEK: μεσίτης (mesitēs, G3316) denotes one who stands between two parties to reconcile them; used of Moses in Gal 3:19-20 but here applied uniquely to Christ as the sole mediator between God and humanity. The apposition ἄνθρωπος Χριστὸς Ἰησοῦς ("the man Christ Jesus") stresses his true humanity as essential to his mediatorial role. DIVINE_COUNCIL: Christ\'s unique mediatorship transcends all angelic or spiritual intermediaries, establishing his singular authority in the divine economy.',
        6: 'GREEK: ἀντίλυτρον (antilytron, G487) is a NT hapax legomenon — found only here. It intensifies λύτρον (lytron, "ransom," cf. Matt 20:28; Mark 10:45) with the prefix ἀντί ("in place of"), emphasizing a substitutionary ransom — a price paid in exchange for another. TYPOLOGY: This echoes the Levitical substitutionary sacrificial system and fulfills the Suffering Servant typology of Isa 53:10-12, where the servant gives his life as an offering for many. The phrase τὸ μαρτύριον καιροῖς ἰδίοις ("the testimony in its own appointed times") indicates that Christ\'s self-giving was revealed according to God\'s sovereign timetable (cf. Gal 4:4; Eph 1:10).',
        12: 'GREEK: αὐθεντεῖν (authentein, G831) is a NT hapax legomenon, appearing only here. Its precise meaning is debated: it may range from "to exercise authority" to "to domineer" or "to usurp authority." The rarity of the term makes definitive conclusions difficult, but the context pairs it with διδάσκειν (didaskein, "to teach"), suggesting a specific ecclesial function rather than a general social principle. HISTORICAL: In the Ephesian context, the cult of Artemis and various Gnostic-leaning teachings may have given rise to women propagating false doctrine (cf. 1 Tim 1:3-7; 2 Tim 3:6-7), which may inform the specificity of this instruction.',
        15: 'THEOLOGICAL: This is among the most debated verses in the Pauline corpus. "The childbearing" (τῆς τεκνογονίας, tēs teknogonias, G5042) carries the definite article τῆς, suggesting not childbearing in general but a specific childbearing. TYPOLOGY: Many interpreters see an allusion to the protoevangelium of Gen 3:15 — the "seed of the woman" who would crush the serpent\'s head — thus pointing to the birth of Christ as the means of salvation that reverses Eve\'s transgression. The shift from singular σωθήσεται ("she shall be saved") to plural μείνωσιν ("they remain") likely broadens the application from Eve (or womankind collectively) to all women who persevere in faith, love, holiness, and self-control.',
    },
    3: {
        1: 'GREEK: "Pistos ho logos" (Πιστὸς ὁ λόγος) is a distinctive Pastoral Epistles formula appearing five times (1 Tim 1:15; 3:1; 4:9; 2 Tim 2:11; Titus 3:8). "Episkopēs" (ἐπισκοπῆς, Strong\'s G1984) means "oversight" or "visitation," from episkopos (overseer). "Oregetai" (ὀρέγεται, G3713) means "stretches out toward" or "aspires to," indicating active, deliberate desire rather than passive wish.',
        2: 'GREEK: "Episkopon" (ἐπίσκοπον, G1985) means "overseer" — one who watches over. The term was used in the LXX for appointed officials and in Greek civic life for municipal supervisors. "Anepilēmpton" (ἀνεπίλημπτον, G423) is literally "not to be laid hold of," meaning one against whom no charge can be seized upon. THEOLOGICAL: The qualifications center on observable character rather than spiritual gifting, emphasizing that leadership in God\'s household requires proven moral integrity visible to all.',
        5: 'THEOLOGICAL: Paul draws a direct analogy between household governance and ecclesial governance. The "oikos" (household) of a man typologically mirrors the "ekklēsia theou" (assembly of God). This reflects the broader biblical pattern where faithfulness in smaller stewardship qualifies one for greater stewardship (Luke 16:10). STRUCTURE: The parenthetical rhetorical question employs an a fortiori (lesser-to-greater) argument.',
        6: 'GREEK: "Neophyton" (νεόφυτον, G3504) is literally "newly planted" — a horticultural metaphor unique in the NT (hapax legomenon). "Typhōtheis" (τυφωθείς, G5187) means "beclouded" or "wrapped in smoke," hence "puffed up with conceit." THEOLOGICAL: The "krima tou diabolou" (judgment of the devil) likely means the same judgment that the devil himself received — pride leading to condemnation. This echoes the divine council theme of a heavenly being falling through self-exaltation (Isa 14:12-15; Ezek 28:17).',
        9: 'GREEK: "Mystērion" (μυστήριον, G3466) here denotes not a hidden secret but divine truth now revealed through the gospel — the mystery of the faith. THEOLOGICAL: The deacon must hold the revealed content of the faith with a "kathara syneidēsei" (clean conscience), binding right doctrine inseparably to right living. Orthodoxy without moral integrity disqualifies one from service.',
        11: 'GREEK: "Gynaikas" (γυναῖκας) can mean either "women" or "wives." Debate persists whether Paul refers to deacons\' wives, women deacons (deaconesses), or a distinct female office. The parallel structure with "hōsautōs" (likewise) mirrors v.8, suggesting a comparable category of service. "Diabolous" (διαβόλους, G1228) here means "slanderers" — the same root as "diabolos" (devil), literally "one who throws across" accusations.',
        15: 'THEOLOGICAL: The "oikos theou" (household of God) is identified as the "ekklēsia theou zōntos" (assembly of the living God). Paul then applies two architectural metaphors: "stylos" (pillar, G4769) and "hedraiōma" (foundation or buttress, G1477 — hapax legomenon in NT). The assembly bears and upholds the truth as a pillar supports a temple. TYPOLOGY: The pillar imagery echoes the temple pillars Jachin and Boaz (1 Kgs 7:21) and the eschatological promise that the faithful will be made a pillar in God\'s temple (Rev 3:12).',
        16: 'GREEK: The textual variant here is significant: the earliest manuscripts read "hos" (Ὅς, "He who") rather than the later "theos" (God) or "ho" (which). The six-line confessional hymn follows a pattern of paired contrasts (flesh/Spirit, angels/nations, world/glory). THEOLOGICAL: This is among the earliest christological hymns, confessing Christ\'s incarnation ("manifested in flesh"), vindication ("justified in Spirit"), angelic revelation ("seen by angels"), global proclamation ("proclaimed among nations"), faith response ("believed on in the world"), and heavenly exaltation ("taken up in glory"). DIVINE_COUNCIL: "Was seen by angels" places Christ\'s work within the divine council framework — the heavenly beings themselves witnessed and were made subject to the revelation of the incarnate Lord (cf. Eph 3:10; 1 Pet 1:12).',
    },
    4: {
        1: 'GREEK: "πνεύμασι πλάνοις" (pneumasin planois) — "deceiving spirits" or "wandering spirits." The adjective planos (G4108) carries the sense of roaming or leading astray, used also of the "deceiving spirit" in the LXX tradition. DIVINE_COUNCIL: Paul here acknowledges a spiritual realm of hostile entities — demons actively producing doctrinal systems ("teachings of demons") channeled through human agents. This reflects the Second Temple understanding of rebellious divine-council members who lead nations and individuals into apostasy (cf. Deut 32:17; Ps 106:37; 1 Cor 10:20).',
        2: 'GREEK: "κεκαυστηριασμένων" (kekaustēriasmenōn, G2743) is a perfect passive participle meaning "having been branded" or "seared as with a hot iron." This is a NT hapax legomenon. The perfect tense indicates a completed action with lasting effect — their conscience has been permanently cauterized, rendering them insensible to moral conviction. The imagery may evoke the Roman practice of branding slaves or criminals.',
        3: 'THEOLOGICAL: The false teachers impose ascetic prohibitions — forbidding marriage and commanding abstinence from foods — that contradict the creational goodness affirmed in Genesis 1. Paul\'s phrase "which God created for reception with thanksgiving" (εἰς μετάλημψιν μετὰ εὐχαριστίας) grounds the argument in creation theology: God\'s good gifts are not to be refused but received with gratitude. HISTORICAL: Such proto-gnostic or encratite tendencies were present in the Ephesian milieu, reflecting dualistic views that denigrated the material world.',
        5: 'GREEK: "ἐντεύξεως" (enteuxeōs, G1783) — "intercession" or "prayer." This term appears only here and in 1 Tim 2:1 in the NT. The sanctification of created things occurs through two means: the word of God (logos theou) and prayer. THEOLOGICAL: This establishes a sacramental principle — the material creation is consecrated not by its own nature alone but through God\'s spoken word and the prayer of the faithful (cf. Gen 1:31).',
        9: 'STRUCTURE: "Faithful is the word" (πιστὸς ὁ λόγος) is one of the five "faithful sayings" unique to the Pastoral Epistles (1 Tim 1:15; 3:1; 4:9; 2 Tim 2:11; Titus 3:8). Scholars debate whether this formula points backward to v.8 or forward to v.10; the context favors a reference to v.8\'s promise regarding godliness, though the connection to the hope expressed in v.10 is also strong.',
        10: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Savior of all men, especially of those who believe" (σωτὴρ πάντων ἀνθρώπων μάλιστα πιστῶν) — "especially" (μάλιστα, G3122) does not negate the universal scope but intensifies the particular application. God\'s saving provision extends universally in its offer and preserving goodness, but is realized eschatologically and salvifically "especially" in those who believe. GREEK: "ζῶντι" (zōnti) — "living" — stands in deliberate contrast to the dead idols and deceiving spirits of vv.1-2; the living God alone is Savior.',
        12: 'GREEK: "τύπος" (typos, G5179) — literally "a strike-mark," hence "pattern, model, example." Timothy is to be a visible imprint of Christlike character for the believing community. HISTORICAL: Timothy\'s youth (νεότης, neotēs) would have been culturally significant in Greco-Roman society, where authority was typically vested in older men. Paul counters potential dismissal not by asserting Timothy\'s rights but by calling him to exemplary living across five domains: word, conduct, love, faith, and purity.',
        14: 'THEOLOGICAL: The "charisma" (χάρισμα, G5486) given to Timothy came through a dual instrumentality: prophetic utterance and the corporate laying on of hands by the presbyterion (πρεσβυτέριον, G4244), the council of elders. This reflects early church ordination practice where the Spirit\'s gifting is mediated through the prophetic community and confirmed by eldership authority (cf. Acts 13:1-3; 2 Tim 1:6). GREEK: πρεσβυτέριον denotes not individual elders but the collective body or council of elders, a term borrowed from Jewish synagogue governance.',
    },
    5: {
        3: 'GREEK: "Honor" (τίμα, timáō, Strong\'s G5091) carries connotations of both respect and material support, as the same root appears in v17 for "double honor" applied to elders. "Truly widows" (ὄντως χήρας) distinguishes those genuinely destitute from those with family resources—a technical category for the early assembly\'s care system.',
        5: 'THEOLOGICAL: The portrait of the "true widow" echoes the prophetess Anna (Luke 2:36-37), who likewise devoted herself to prayer and fasting in the temple night and day. The perfect tense "has set her hope" (ἤλπικεν) indicates a settled, abiding state of trust in God, not a momentary disposition.',
        8: 'THEOLOGICAL: Paul employs the strongest possible language: denying the faith (τὴν πίστιν ἤρνηται) and being worse than an unbeliever (ἀπίστου χείρων). This grounds household provision not merely in social convention but in the very nature of covenant faithfulness. Even pagans in the Greco-Roman world recognized familial obligation.',
        10: 'GREEK: "Brought up children" (ἐτεκνοτρόφησεν, teknotrophéō, G5044) is a hapax legomenon in the NT. "Showed hospitality to strangers" (ἐξενοδόχησεν, xenodochéō, G3580) is likewise a NT hapax. The washing of saints\' feet recalls Jesus\' act of humble service (John 13:5-14), suggesting that the enrolled widow embodies Christlike servanthood.',
        14: 'GREEK: "The adversary" (τῷ ἀντικειμένῳ) is a present middle participle meaning "the one who opposes," which could refer to Satan or to human opponents of the faith. THEOLOGICAL: Paul\'s counsel is pastoral and strategic—minimizing occasion for slander against the assembly. "Guide the household" (οἰκοδεσποτεῖν, G3616) is another NT hapax, granting the wife significant domestic authority.',
        17: 'GREEK: "Rule well" (καλῶς προεστῶτες) uses proïstēmi (G4291), meaning to stand before, lead, or manage. "Double honor" (διπλῆς τιμῆς) almost certainly includes financial remuneration, as v18 immediately supports this with Scripture. The distinction "especially those laboring in word and teaching" implies not all elders held a primary teaching function.',
        18: 'TYPOLOGY: Paul cites Deuteronomy 25:4 (LXX) alongside a saying attributed to the Lord Jesus (Luke 10:7), placing both on equal footing as "Scripture" (ἡ γραφή). This is a significant witness to the early recognition of apostolic and dominical words as carrying Scriptural authority alongside the Torah.',
        21: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: The solemn charge is made "before God and Christ Jesus and the elect angels" (τῶν ἐκλεκτῶν ἀγγέλων). This tripartite witness formula invokes the divine council as the heavenly tribunal before which Timothy\'s ministry will be judged. "Elect angels" distinguishes faithful heavenly beings from fallen ones, reflecting the cosmic dimension of ecclesial governance. GREEK: "Prejudgment" (πρόκριμα, prókrima, G4299) is a NT hapax, meaning a verdict rendered before hearing the case.',
        22: 'THEOLOGICAL: The laying on of hands (χεῖρας ἐπιτίθει) likely refers to ordination of elders, connecting back to the instructions about elder discipline in vv17-20. Hasty ordination implicates one in the sins that an unvetted leader may commit. "Keep yourself pure" (σεαυτὸν ἁγνὸν τήρει) forms a bookend with the purity theme introduced in v2.',
        24: 'THEOLOGICAL: This proverbial observation provides the theological rationale for patient discernment in vv21-22. Some sins are immediately manifest; others surface only later. Therefore both hasty ordination and hasty accusation are dangerous. The eschatological dimension of "judgment" (κρίσιν) reminds Timothy that God\'s final assessment will reveal all hidden things (Rom 2:16; 1 Cor 4:5).',
    },
    6: {
        1: 'GREEK: "Under a yoke" (ὑπὸ ζυγόν, hypo zygon) is a metaphor for the condition of servitude. "Bondservants" (δοῦλοι, douloi, Strong\'s G1401) denotes slaves in the Roman household system. "Masters" (δεσπότας, despotas, Strong\'s G1203) differs from κύριος and specifically denotes absolute ownership. HISTORICAL: Paul addresses the social reality of slavery within the Roman Empire, where an estimated one-third of the population were enslaved. The concern is that dishonoring pagan masters would bring reproach upon the gospel.',
        4: 'GREEK: "Puffed up with conceit" (τετύφωται, tetyphōtai, Strong\'s G5187) literally means "wrapped in smoke" or "beclouded"—a vivid metaphor for intellectual delusion. "Word-battles" (λογομαχίας, logomachias, Strong\'s G3055) is a compound of λόγος + μάχη and is a NT hapax legomenon, describing contentious verbal disputes that produce no edification.',
        6: 'THEOLOGICAL: This verse stands as a pivotal counter-thesis to the false teachers\' equation of godliness with material profit (v.5). "Contentment" (αὐταρκείας, autarkeias, Strong\'s G841) was a key Stoic virtue meaning self-sufficiency, but Paul redefines it as sufficiency found in God rather than in oneself (cf. Phil 4:11-12). True gain (πορισμός, porismos) is godliness accompanied by this God-centered satisfaction.',
        10: 'GREEK: "Love of money" (φιλαργυρία, philargyria, Strong\'s G5365) is a compound of φίλος (love) + ἀργύριον (silver). Note Paul writes "a root" (ῥίζα, rhiza, without the article in some manuscripts), not necessarily "the root"—money-love is one fundamental root among evils, not the sole origin of all evil. "Pierced themselves through" (περιέπειραν, periepeiran, Strong\'s G4044) is another NT hapax legomenon, depicting a violent self-inflicted impaling on sorrows.',
        12: 'GREEK: "Fight" (ἀγωνίζου, agōnizou) and "fight" (ἀγῶνα, agōna) form a cognate accusative construction—literally "agonize the good agony." The athletic imagery evokes the Greek games. THEOLOGICAL: "Lay hold" (ἐπιλαβοῦ, epilabou) is an aorist imperative suggesting decisive, urgent action. The eternal life is both a present possession and a future hope to be grasped. Timothy\'s "good confession" likely refers to his baptismal confession or ordination vow (cf. v.13; 2 Tim 1:6).',
        13: 'THEOLOGICAL: The solemn charge invokes both God the Father as life-giver (ζῳογονοῦντος, zōogonountos—the one who gives life to all things, echoing creation and resurrection power) and Christ Jesus as the faithful witness. HISTORICAL: The reference to Pontius Pilate anchors the faith in concrete history. Christ\'s "good confession" before Pilate (John 18:36-37) serves as the paradigm for Timothy\'s own faithfulness under pressure. TYPOLOGY: As Christ confessed before the earthly ruler, so Timothy must confess before his generation—the pattern of faithful witness unto potential suffering.',
        15: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Blessed and only Sovereign" (μακάριος καὶ μόνος δυνάστης) is a doxological title applied to God who orchestrates the appearing of Christ. "King of those reigning and Lord of those exercising lordship" (βασιλεὺς τῶν βασιλευόντων καὶ κύριος τῶν κυριευόντων) directly challenges Roman imperial claims to supreme authority (cf. Rev 17:14; 19:16). DIVINE_COUNCIL: This title asserts God\'s absolute sovereignty over all rulers, both human and spiritual—all powers, thrones, and dominions are subordinate to the one true Sovereign. The "own times" (καιροῖς ἰδίοις) emphasizes divine prerogative over eschatological timing.',
        16: 'GREEK: "Unapproachable" (ἀπρόσιτον, aprositon, Strong\'s G676) is a NT hapax legomenon—light so radiant that no mortal can draw near. THEOLOGICAL: "The only one having immortality" (ὁ μόνος ἔχων ἀθανασίαν) does not deny that believers receive immortality, but affirms that God alone possesses it intrinsically and inherently. This echoes the theophany traditions of the Old Testament where God\'s glory is unbearable to human sight (Exod 33:20; 1 Kgs 8:11). The language forms a barrier between Creator and creature that only divine revelation can bridge.',
        19: 'TYPOLOGY: "Treasuring up a good foundation" (ἀποθησαυρίζοντας θεμέλιον καλόν) mixes metaphors of treasure-storing and foundation-laying, echoing Jesus\' teaching on storing treasures in heaven (Matt 6:19-20) and building on a firm foundation (Matt 7:24-25). GREEK: "That which is truly life" (τῆς ὄντως ζωῆς) uses the adverb ὄντως (ontōs, "really, truly") to distinguish authentic eternal life from mere biological or material existence.',
        20: 'GREEK: "The deposit" (παραθήκην, parathēkēn, Strong\'s G3866) is a legal-banking term for something entrusted to another for safekeeping—here the apostolic teaching and sound doctrine entrusted to Timothy. "Falsely-named knowledge" (ψευδωνύμου γνώσεως) is a direct polemic; ψευδώνυμος (pseudōnymos, Strong\'s G5581) means "bearing a false name." HISTORICAL: This likely targets early forms of proto-Gnostic speculation or syncretistic Jewish-Hellenistic speculative systems circulating in Ephesus, which claimed superior "knowledge" (gnōsis) while contradicting apostolic teaching.',
    },
}